NAGECO signed a non-binding letter of intent with TGS, a unit of Libya’s NOC', 'Norwegian geophysical data company TGS said it has signed a letter of intent with North Africa Geophysical Company (NAGECO), a subsidiary of Libya’s National Oil Corporation.

In a Jan. 30 statement, TGS said the letter sets out a framework for future cooperation between the two parties in the field of seismic and geophysical data used in oil and gas exploration.

The document is non-binding and remains subject to the negotiation of definitive agreements and the receipt of required regulatory approvals. TGS said the initiative focuses on developing exploration data intended for use by multiple oil companies operating in Libya, in order to support upstream oil and gas activities.

The announcement is part of a series of recent engagements by TGS across Africa. In 2024, the group was involved in several projects related to seismic data management and provision on the continent, according to Ecofin Agency.

In June of that year, Tanzanian authorities selected TGS to manage offshore seismic data, including 2D and 3D marine surveys, to support the country’s exploration efforts. The momentum continued in July, when the company signed an agreement with Mauritania’s Ministry of Petroleum, Mines, and Energy to supply and enhance geophysical data covering both onshore and offshore areas.

In October 2024, Benin’s authorities also retained TGS for 3D seismic survey work aimed at identifying new offshore exploration prospects.

The latest development comes as Libyan authorities said last week that they are considering launching a second licensing round, as part of initiatives introduced in recent months to support and revive the country’s oil sector.', '/uploads/1774853909822-cae4c45d-857f-4167-8eee-d335ef5cb987.webp', 'PUBLISHED', '2026-03-30 07:02:28.593', '{/uploads/1774853909822-cae4c45d-857f-4167-8eee-d335ef5cb987.webp}', 'News 1News 1News 1News 1News 1', 'News 1News 1News 1News 1News 1', '/uploads/1772694106827-b5d7e34b-07f2-45b7-a76f-bb3e09e8cd8a.jpg', '2026-03-29 12:31:40.154', '2026-03-30 07:02:28.595', 'cmmd40kqs0000qvmfkhfexsk3', 'cmmd40kqs0000qvmfkhfexsk3', 'cmmd40kqs0000qvmfkhfexsk3');
  <article>
    <h1 style="font-size: 2rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
      Four MoUs Signed Between NOC and SONATRACH to Strengthen Joint Cooperation
    </h1>

    <p>
      On Thursday, July 24, 2025, at SONATRACH headquarters in Algiers, four MoUs were signed between the National Oil Corporation (NOC) and Sonatrach to enhance joint cooperation in the fields of petroleum operations and services, training, and expertise exchange.
    </p>

    <p>
      The first MoU, signed between the National Company of Geophysics (ENAGEO), a subsidiary of SONATRACH, and the North African Geophysical Exploration Company (NAGECO), a subsidiary of the NOC, focused on geophysical exploration activities.
    </p>

    <p>
      The second MoU, signed between the National Well Services Company (ENSP), a subsidiary of Sonatrach, and Jowfe Oil Technology (JOT), a subsidiary of the NOC, concerns the provision of petroleum services in Algeria, Libya, and abroad.
    </p>

    <p>
      The third MoU, signed between SONATRACH / Exploration and Production – Laboratories Division and the Petroleum Research Center, concerns laboratory work, analysis, and petroleum research. It aims to conduct joint work within the framework of partnership projects between SONATRACH and the NOC.
    </p>

    <p>
      The fourth MoU, which concerns training and knowledge transfer, was signed between SONATRACH and the National Oil Corporation (NOC). It aims to cooperate in the field of training and know-how transfer in all disciplines related to the oil and gas sector in both countries.
    </p>

    <h2 style="font-size: 1.4rem; margin-top: 2rem;">
      The Libyan side was represented at the signing ceremony by:
    </h2>

    <ul style="padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li>Hussain Safar, Member of the Board of Directors of the NOC and Chairman of the Steering Committee for Joint Cooperation between the NOC and SONATRACH;</li>
      <li>Bashir Garea, Member of the Steering Committee for Joint Cooperation between the NOC and SONATRACH;</li>
      <li>Mohamed Bishr, General Director of the Training and Development Department;</li>
      <li>Faisal Miloud, Director of the Drilling Department;</li>
      <li>Adel Elbay, Secretary of the Steering Committee;</li>
      <li>Khaled Alati, General Manager of the Oil Research Center;</li>
      <li>Nasser Alzawi, Member of the Management Committee of Jowfe Company;</li>
      <li>Majid Alarbed, Chairman of the Management Committee of North African Geophysical Exploration Company.</li>
    </ul>

    <p style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">
      It is worth noting that the signing of these MoUs with SONATRACH reinforces the profound and ongoing strategic partnership between the two parties and demonstrates the NOC’s commitment to developing strong, sustainable, and strategic partnerships with SONATRACH.
    </p>
  </article>
